HOW TO ATTACH AN RJ45 CONNECTOR TO A CAT6 CABLE

Tools Required:
- CAT6 Ethernet cable
- RJ45 (CAT6) connector
- RJ45 crimping tool
- Wire stripper
- Cable tester (recommended)

Step 1:
Cut the CAT6 cable to the required length using a cable cutter.

Step 2:
Strip about 2–3 cm (1 inch) of the outer jacket without damaging the inner wires.

Step 3:
Separate the four twisted wire pairs and straighten the eight individual wires.

Step 4:
Arrange the wires in the T568B wiring order:
Pin 1 - White/Orange
Pin 2 - Orange
Pin 3 - White/Green
Pin 4 - Blue
Pin 5 - White/Blue
Pin 6 - Green
Pin 7 - White/Brown
Pin 8 - Brown

Step 5:
Trim all eight wires evenly so they are the same length.

Step 6:
Insert the wires fully into the RJ45 connector, ensuring each wire reaches the end and the cable jacket is inside the connector.

Step 7:
Place the RJ45 connector into the crimping tool and squeeze the handles firmly to crimp the connector.

Step 8:
Repeat the same T568B wiring order on the other end of the cable to make a straight-through Ethernet cable.

Step 9:
Test the finished cable using a network cable tester to verify all eight wires are connected correctly.

Precautions:
- Do not damage the inner wires while stripping the cable.
- Keep the twisted pairs as close to the connector as possible.
- Use CAT6-compatible RJ45 connectors.
- If the connector is crimped incorrectly, replace it with a new one.

